---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="SS Developers | Cape Town Web Developer for Websites, Apps, and Software" description="I build digital products, internal tools, trading systems, and fintech software for teams that need dependable engineering and clear technical ownership.">
  <section class="hero-section">
    <div class="container hero-layout">
      <div class="hero-text stack-lg" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 40ms;">
        <div class="hero-kicker">
          <span class="hero-kicker-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>Open for focused work</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="hero-title">I build <span class="accent">digital products and custom systems</span> for growth, impact, and stability.</h1>
        <p class="hero-copy">
          I build product sites, web applications, internal tools, and specialist systems where the user experience and the engineering both matter.
          The work is about more than polish: it is about systems that stay reliable as usage grows, data changes, and teams hand the product off.
          That means tighter technical ownership, clearer product behaviour, and code that does not drift once it is live.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a href="/projects" class="button-primary">See my work</a>
          <a href="/contact" class="button-secondary">Start Your Project</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-visual" aria-hidden="true" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 120ms;">
        <img src="/images/redesign/hero-system-surface.png" alt="" class="hero-image" />
        <div class="hero-overlay"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container content-split">
      <div class="visual-panel visual-panel-light" data-reveal>
        <img
          src="/images/redesign/exercise-app-tablet-light.png"
          alt="Light-themed exercise learning app shown on a sleek tablet."
          class="visual-panel-image visual-panel-image-contain"
        />
      </div>

      <div class="section-panel" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 60ms;">
        <div class="section-head">
          <div class="page-intro">How the work starts</div>
          <h2 class="section-title">Education interfaces that hold attention and <span class="accent">stay dependable.</span></h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">
          A calm product surface only works when the state underneath it is trustworthy. I start by defining what the user needs to see clearly, what can drift, and what the system has to keep true without asking the team to babysit it.
        </p>
        <div class="feature-list">
          <div class="feature-list-item">
            <strong>Clear scope before UI polish.</strong>
            <p>I map the states, decisions, and handoffs first so the interface is answering a real operational problem.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="feature-list-item">
            <strong>Working surfaces early.</strong>
            <p>The useful parts of the product show up quickly, which makes feedback more concrete and reduces late-stage surprises.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="feature-list-item">
            <strong>Readable behaviour once live.</strong>
            <p>The end result should stay understandable when content changes, usage grows, or another team has to take ownership.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <a href="/how-i-work" class="link-inline">See how the work runs</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section timeline-tree">
    <div class="container content-split timeline-tree-layout">
      <div class="timeline-list">
        <article class="timeline-card" data-reveal>
          <strong>Websites and product apps</strong>
          <p>Public-facing work that has to explain the product clearly and still hold up once the engineering reality gets more complex.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-card" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 40ms;">
          <strong>Internal tools and system work</strong>
          <p>Operational software for teams that need clearer state, fewer manual gaps, and less guesswork around what the system is doing.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-card" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 80ms;">
          <strong>Trading systems and fintech</strong>
          <p>Builds where reconciliation, execution state, contributions, payouts, or trust-sensitive flows need more care than a standard app cycle.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-card" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 120ms;">
          <strong>Product reliability and ownership</strong>
          <p>Hardening the logic, interfaces, and handoff paths so the product stays legible and dependable after launch.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="visual-panel" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 80ms;">
        <img
          src="/images/redesign/teacher-tracking-tool-tablet.png"
          alt="Operational dashboard for learner tracking shown on a tablet."
          class="visual-panel-image"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section selected-work" id="work">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head section-head--center" data-reveal>
        <div class="page-intro">Selected work</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">Two systems that <span class="accent">show how I think.</span></h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          Both projects deal with trust. One has to keep several moving parts in agreement. The other has to make financial state easy to understand for the people relying on it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="feature-stack">
        <article class="feature-panel" data-reveal>
          <div class="feature-panel-header">
            <div class="stack-lg">
              <div class="eyeline">Trading infrastructure</div>
              <h3 class="feature-title">SMC SuperFIB</h3>
              <p class="panel-copy">
                A cross-runtime trading system that keeps indicator logic, API state, execution clients, and operator visibility aligned.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="project-challenge">The hard part was keeping multiple runtimes in agreement without the operator needing to read raw logs to understand what was happening.</p>
          <a href="/projects/superfib" class="link-inline">Read the SuperFIB case study</a>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-panel" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 70ms;">
          <div class="feature-panel-header">
            <div class="stack-lg">
              <div class="eyeline">Community finance</div>
              <h3 class="feature-title">Stokvel Society</h3>
              <p class="panel-copy">
                A fintech product for contributions, ledger visibility, and payout flows that members can actually follow.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="project-challenge">The hard part was turning a trust-heavy community finance workflow into software that feels calm, clear, and dependable.</p>
          <a href="/projects/stokvel" class="link-inline">Read the Stokvel Society case study</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section next-step" id="contact">
    <div class="container next-step-shell">
      <div class="section-panel next-step-copy" data-reveal>
        <div class="page-intro">Next step</div>
        <h2 class="section-title">See the work, then decide if the <span class="accent">fit is right.</span></h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          If the system has to stay understandable and dependable once it is live, the case studies will tell you quickly whether the fit is there.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="next-step-actions" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 60ms;">
        <a href="/projects" class="button-primary">See my work</a>
        <a href="/contact" class="button-secondary">Start Your Project</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
